{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521335"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.2,0.11,0.16,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6194"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92239"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of chest pain and shortness of breath following the unexpected death of her spouse. She describes the pain as \u0022crushing\u0022 and radiating to her left arm. She has a medical history of hypertension and chronic gastritis. She does not take any regular medications. She denies any previous cardiac history, although she has a family history of coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 165/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her current ECG is shown (Image). A previous ECG is obtained from her General Practitioner, performed during a routine health maintenance visit two months ago, and is normal. An initial troponin is elevated. An urgent bedside echocardiogram reveals hypokinesis of the apical segments with preserved basal function, suggestive of apical ballooning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After analgesia, which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate coronary angiography","High-dose beta-blocker therapy","Start an ACE inhibitor","Administer a loading dose of clopidogrel","Intravenous nitroglycerin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate coronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because the patient\u0027s symptoms are suggestive of an acute coronary syndrome given the chest pain description, ECG changes (new left bundle branch block), and elevated troponin. However, the echocardiographic findings of apical ballooning are characteristic of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy. This condition mimics acute coronary syndrome and is often triggered by acute stress, as seen in this patient\u0027s case after a significant personal loss. Coronary angiography is crucial here to exclude obstructive coronary disease and confirm Takotsubo cardiomyopathy. In scenarios where coronary artery disease is confirmed, this approach would guide towards revascularization.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETakotsubo cardiomyopathy, also known as stress-induced cardiomyopathy or broken heart syndrome, is characterized by transient left ventricular dysfunction, often affecting the apex of the heart (hence the term \u0027apical ballooning\u0027), in the absence of significant coronary artery stenosis. It typically occurs in postmenopausal women and is frequently preceded by an emotional or physical stressor. The exact pathophysiology is not fully understood, but catecholamine surge is thought to play a significant role.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETakotsubo Cardiomyopathy can be associated with ECG changes such as ST elevation or t-wave inversion in the anterior leads or a new LBBB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose beta-blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in managing ongoing symptoms in confirmed cases of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy due to their effect in reducing heart rate and myocardial oxygen consumption. However, they are not indicated initially without coronary angiography, as inappropriate use could potentially worsen outcomes if there is concomitant obstructive coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EACE inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly indicated in chronic heart failure management and after myocardial infarction to improve cardiac function. However, in the acute setting of suspected Takotsubo cardiomyopathy without heart failure symptoms or confirmed myocardial infarction, it is premature to start an ACE inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoading dose of clopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in acute coronary syndromes where a thrombotic cause is confirmed or highly suspected, especially when percutaneous coronary intervention is planned. In this case, without confirming the presence of coronary artery disease, this management could lead to unnecessary anticoagulation complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous nitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E, While it is commonly used to manage chest pain, particularly in suspected acute coronary syndrome, it may lead to hypotension and exacerbate ventricular outflow tract obstruction in cases like Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, where no coronary obstruction is present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate coronary angiography is vital in cases presenting with symptoms suggestive of acute coronary syndrome but with findings indicative of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, as it is essential to rule out obstructive coronary pathology and accurately diagnose the condition to guide appropriate management.","Takotsubo cardiomyopathy is characterised by transient left ventricular dysfunction, often triggered by emotional or physical stress, and can mimic acute coronary syndrome."],"references":["Segan L, Vlachadis Castles A, Fendel K, McFarlane L, Vaddadi G, Amerena J. P812 Takotsubo cardiomyopathy: phenotypic diversity and contemporary management. European Heart Journal. 2019 Oct 1;40(Supplement_1):ehz747-0411.                                                                                      https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehz747.0411","Liauw SS, Liu S, Bastiany A. Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy. Biology of Women\u2019s Heart Health. 2023 Nov 19:55-74.                                                                    https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-39928-2_5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92239"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20727"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20727"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aPrOiJ1oknOgN8xsxMLwrIcYC5QqiZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aPrOiJ1oknOgN8xsxMLwrIcYC5QqiZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":761,"height":368}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92239","links":{"se